  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      A recently isolated peptide hormone, hepcidin, is thought to be the principal regulator of
      iron homeostasis. Hepcidin acts by limiting intestinal iron absorption and promoting iron
      retention in reticuloendothelial cells. The aims of this study were to determine serum
      hepcidin levels in preterm infants who receive blood transfusion and preterm infants having
      sepsis, in order to assess possible relationships between hepcidin and serum iron, serum
      ferritin,in iron load situations.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
